This is the Gaussian integral. Let $I = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} e^{-x^2} dx$.
Then $I^2 = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} e^{-x^2} dx \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} e^{-y^2} dy = \iint_{\mathbb{R}^2} e^{-(x^2+y^2)} dx dy$.
Switching to polar coordinates: $x = r \cos \theta, y = r \sin \theta, dx dy = r dr d\theta$.
$I^2 = \int_{0}^{2\pi} d\theta \int_{0}^{\infty} e^{-r^2} r dr = 2\pi \left[ -\frac{1}{2} e^{-r^2} \right]_{0}^{\infty} = 2\pi (0 - (-\frac{1}{2})) = \pi$.
Thus $I = \sqrt{\pi}$.
Since $e^{-t^2}$ is even, $\int_{0}^{\infty} e^{-t^2} dt = \frac{1}{2} \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} e^{-t^2} dt = \frac{\sqrt{\pi}}{2}$.
Therefore, $\lim_{x \to \infty} f(x) = \frac{\sqrt{\pi}}{2}$.
